         <div type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
            <div type="textpart" n="1">
               <p>Свет <supplied reason="lost">Христов</supplied> светит всем.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="textpart" n="2">
               <p>Почила <supplied reason="lost">ра</supplied>ба <supplied reason="lost">Божья Ев</supplied>троп<supplied reason="lost">ия. Поч</supplied>ил и раб Божий <supplied reason="lost">такой-то</supplied> (или: <supplied reason="lost">Поч</supplied>ила и раб<supplied reason="lost">а</supplied> Божья <supplied reason="lost">такая-то</supplied>).</p>
            </div>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
            <div type="textpart" n="1">
               <p>The light <supplied reason="lost">of Christ</supplied> shines for all.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="textpart" n="2">
               <p>Fell asleep: a servant [of God, Eu]tropia. <supplied reason="lost">Fell</supplied> asleep also a servant of God...</p>
            </div>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary" xml:lang="ru">
            <div type="textpart" n="1">
               <p>Относительно формулы см. <ref type="introduction">IV.3.C.a</ref>.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="textpart" n="2">
               <p> 1–2. Относительно формулы см. <ref type="introduction">IV.3.F.e</ref>.</p>
                <p> 2–3. Имя Евтропия, легко читающееся и на фотографии, опубликованной у Латышева, встречается на Боспоре в мужском варианте 
                   Евтропий (<ref type="inscription">V 273</ref><!--byz261-->). Известны две мученицы с таким именем (см. Delehaye 1902, 1086).</p>
               <p>Внешний облик памятника находит аналогии в поздневизантийских надгробиях Горного Крыма (ср., напр., <ref type="inscription">V 141</ref><!--byz136-->, 1301 г.) и 
                  Алушты (<ref type="inscription">V 234</ref><!--byz221-->, XIV в.).</p>
            </div>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
            <div type="textpart" n="1">
               <p>On the formula, see Introduction <ref type="introduction">IV.3.C.a</ref>.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="textpart" n="2">
               <p> 1–2. On the formula, see Introduction <ref type="introduction">IV.3.F.e</ref>.</p>
               <p> 2–3. The name Eutropia which is easy to discern on the photograph published by Latyshev, is known in Bosporus in masculine form
                  Eutropios (<ref type="inscription">V 273</ref><!--byz261-->). Two martyresses of this name are know (see Delehaye 1902, 1086).</p>
               <p>The style of the monument is silimar to Late Byzantine tombstones of Mountainous Crimea (see, e.g., <ref type="inscription">V 141</ref><!--byz136--> 1301 C.E.) 
                  and of Alushta (<ref type="inscription">V 234</ref><!--byz221-->, XIVth century) </p>
               <p/>
            </div>
         </div>
